# Jira via Atlassian MCP (mandatory)

**Jira is the source of truth** for planning, orchestration, implementation, QA and security findings, documentation tasks, execution tracking, ownership, and PR lifecycle. When the **Atlassian MCP** is enabled and reachable, agents **must** use MCP tools for every Jira interaction. Agents **must not** simulate, invent, or hand-wave Jira operations (fake keys, imaginary transitions, or “I would update Jira” without an MCP call).

## Required MCP-backed operations

Use Atlassian MCP tools (names may vary by plugin version) for:

- Creating, reading, and editing issues
- Workflow transitions (e.g. To Do → **In Progress** → **In Review** → Done)
- Search (JQL)
- Comments, labels, fields, links between issues
- Worklogs or other project-standard fields when required by the team

If MCP is **unavailable** (auth failure, disabled server): state that explicitly, stop claiming Jira was updated, and ask the human to fix MCP or perform the Jira change—do not pretend the operation succeeded.

## Separation of concerns (three layers)

| Layer | Agent | Jira / execution role |
|--------|--------|------------------------|
| **Planning** | **technical-planning-agent** | Creates **Epics** and **Stories** via MCP, dependency map, roadmap; **never** implements product code or opens PRs. **Stops** after Jira + handoff. |
| **Orchestration** | **orchestrator-agent** | Reads backlog via MCP, sequences work, assigns **workers**, transitions **In Progress** / verifies **In Review**; does **not** replace the planner for initial Epic/story authoring. |
| **Implementation** | **Worker agents** | Implement from assigned stories only; PRs + tests + docs; MCP for story read/update. |

## technical-planning-agent

- **Read-only** architecture analysis is permitted; **no** product source edits, **no** feature implementation, **no** PRs, **no** QA test implementation for the initiative—**Jira + roadmap only**.
- For **medium/large** initiatives: create a detailed **Epic** via MCP (business + technical context, architecture, goals, risks, execution and orchestration strategy, testing and deployment considerations).
- **Planning is not complete** until **Epic (if required)** and **every story** exist in Jira **via MCP**, with rich descriptions: **Business context (WHY)**, **Technical context (HOW)**, Objective, Scope, **Implementation guidance** (non-code), Acceptance criteria, Testing requirements, Documentation requirements, Dependencies, Risks, Recommended worker agent, Suggested PR boundary, Ownership scope.
- Link stories to the Epic and each other via MCP (`createIssueLink`, etc.). **Do not** simulate Jira.
- After Jira and handoff: **stop**—do not orchestrate or implement.

## orchestrator-agent

- Read backlog and dependencies via MCP (`getJiraIssue`, `searchJiraIssuesUsingJql`, links).
- Do **not** dispatch a worker to a story that is blocked by unresolved dependencies.
- Do **not** assign **more than one** concurrent implementation worker to the **same** story.
- When a story is **selected for execution** and a worker is **assigned or spawned**, **immediately** transition that issue to **In Progress** via MCP (`getTransitionsForJiraIssue` then `transitionJiraIssue` or equivalent).
- Do not leave stories that are actively being implemented stuck in **To Do**.
- Track progress with MCP (comments, status, links); keep Jira aligned with reality.

## Worker agents (implementation)

Applies to: **data-engineering-agent**, **backend-agent**, **frontend-agent**, **data-scientist-agent**, **data-analyst-agent** (and any other role explicitly treated as implementation workers by the orchestrator).

- **Read** the assigned story via MCP before coding.
- Implement **only** that story’s scope; respect **ownership** boundaries and Cursor hooks (`OWNERSHIP=...` on Task where required).
- One implementation PR **maps to exactly one** Jira story; include tests and required docs; structured PR body (summary, risks, impacted components).
- When implementation is complete, tests and docs are done, and the PR exists: transition the story to **In Review** via MCP.

Worker agents **must not**: combine multiple stories in one PR, edit unrelated components to “save time,” or bypass orchestration governance. They **must not** author initiative-level **Epics** or full **story backlogs** that replace **technical-planning-agent**—escalate gaps to the planner/orchestrator.

## Specialist agents (QA, security, documentation, code-review)

These agents **must not** replace **technical-planning-agent** for initiative-wide **Epic** or full **story backlog** design. They create **targeted** follow-on issues (bugs, findings, doc tasks) linked to existing Epic/story work.

## qa-agent

- Validate behavior, edges, pipelines, coverage, and regression safety.
- On defects: create **bug** issues via MCP with reproduction, severity, risks, and **links** to the related story or PR.

## security-agent

- Review security posture, dependencies, secrets handling, deployment safety.
- On issues: create **security** issues via MCP with remediation guidance and links to impacted stories or components.

## documentation-agent

- Maintain READMEs, architecture docs, ADRs, and runbooks.
- When gaps require tracked work: create **documentation** stories via MCP.

## Planning vs implementation (Jira ownership)

**Planning and orchestration** agents may run **before** stories exist (they create or coordinate work). **Implementation** workers must always be **story-driven** and Jira-backed via MCP as above.

## PR hygiene

Every implementation PR must: map to a **single** Jira story, stay in **ownership** scope, include **tests**, and use a structured description (summary, risk, impacted systems). Align PR title/body with the Jira key for traceability.
